{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox settlement | name = Berestechko | native_name = {{lang|uk|Берестечко}} | other_name = {{lang|pl|Beresteczko}} {{in lang|pl}} | settlement_type = City | nickname = | motto = | image_skyline = Beresteczko sobor.jpg | image_caption = Church of the Holy Trinity | image_flag =Berestechko h.gif | image_seal = Berestechko s.gif | seal_caption = | pushpin_map = Ukraine Volyn Oblast#Ukraine | image_map = | map_caption = | subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]] | subdivision_name = {{UKR}} | subdivision_type1 = [[Oblasts of Ukraine|Oblast]] | subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Volyn Oblast}} | subdivision_type2 = [[Raions of Ukraine|Raion]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Horokhiv Raion]] | leader_title = Mayor | leader_name = Mykola Shotik | population_as_of = 2018 | population_total = 1711<ref>Чисельність наявного населення України на 1 січня 2018 року. Державна служба статистики України. Київ, 2018. стор.15</ref> | coordinates = {{coord|50|21|00|N|25|07|00|E|region:UA|display=inline,title}} | elevation = | website = http://berestechko.in.ua | footnotes = }} '''Berestechko''' ({{lang-uk|Берестечко}}; {{lang-pl|Beresteczko}}) is a town in [[Horokhiv Raion]], [[Volyn Oblast]], Ukraine.
It is located on the [[Styr River]].
== History == Berestechko received [[Magdeburg rights]] in 1547.
In 1651 the [[Battle of Berestechko]] took place near the settlement<ref name=autogenerated1>Берестечко // Большая Советская Энциклопедия. / редколл., гл. ред. С. И. Вавилов. 2-е изд. том 5. М., Государственное научное издательство «Большая Советская энциклопедия», 1950. стр.12</ref>.
From 1795 until the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Russian Revolution]] of 1917, Berestechko was part of [[Volhynian Governorate]] of the [[Russian Empire]]; from 1921 to 1939 it was part of [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]].
Since September 1939 it was a part of the [[USSR]], town since January 1940<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>Берестечко // Большой энциклопедический словарь (в 2-х тт.). / редколл., гл. ред. А. М. Прохоров. том 1. М., "Советская энциклопедия", 1991. стр.129</ref>.
The Germans occupied Berestechko from 1941 to April 1944, during which they executed Jews from the town. A witness to the execution in the town stated, "The Jews dug their own pits, accompanied by ten requisitioned Ukrainians. People climbed on trees to watch the execution In spite of the ban. The Germans shot them so that they fell down into the pit."<ref>{{cite web|title=Yahad-In Unum Interactive Map|url=http://yahadmap.org/#village/berestechko-volyn-ukraine.14|website=Execution Sites of Jewish Victims Investigated by Yahad-In Unum|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>
A monastery once located near Berestechko was razed by the [[Soviet army]]{{source?|date=May 2019}}.
